<h2 class="header"><i>1</i>Graph matchings<a class="headerlink" href="#graph-matchings" name="graph-matchings">&para;</a></h2>
<h3 class="header"><i>1.1</i>Stable marriage<a class="headerlink" href="#stable-marriage" name="stable-marriage">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Gale-Shapley: male choice method, male-optimal, female-pessimal (lemma: no woman leaves/rejects a valid partner)</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>1.2</i>Matching cardinality<a class="headerlink" href="#matching-cardinality" name="matching-cardinality">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Match <span>$M$</span> is maximal <span>$\iff$</span> no augmenting path for <span>$M$</span>. Proof: (<span>$\Rightarrow$</span>) just switch <span>$M$</span> and not <span>$M$</span> in the path. (<span>$\Leftarrow$</span>) Symmetric diff with <span>$M$</span> and <span>$M^*$</span> (a theoretical maximal matching); all vertices have deg <span>$\leq 2$</span>, so there are only disjoint paths and cycles. Specifically, we have even-length paths, even-length cycles, and odd-length paths ending in <span>$M^*$</span> - but the latter is augmenting wrt <span>$M$</span>.</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>1.3</i>Bipartite graphs<a class="headerlink" href="#bipartite-graphs" name="bipartite-graphs">&para;</a></h3>
<p>No odd cycles. Can be separated into 2 groups, each edge spans both.</p>
<h4 class="header"><i>1.3.1</i>Hall's theorem<a class="headerlink" href="#halls-theorem" name="halls-theorem">&para;</a></h4>
<p>Bipartite graph has a PM <span>$\iff$</span> <span>$\forall A \subseteq X$</span>, <span>$|\Gamma(A)| \geq |A|$</span>. Proof: sort of by induction on <span>$X$</span>, it's weird</p>
<h4 class="header"><i>1.3.2</i>Regular graphs<a class="headerlink" href="#regular-graphs" name="regular-graphs">&para;</a></h4>
<p><span>$d$</span>-regular: all vertices have <span>$\deg d$</span>. Any <span>$d$</span>-reg bipartite graph can be decomposed into <span>$d$</span> edge-disjoint PMs. Proof by induction: if it has a PM <span>$M$</span>, can apply IH to <span>$G-M$</span> (since it's <span>$(d-1)$</span>-regular) and then throw <span>$M$</span> back in there. To prove it has a PM, show that Hall's holds.</p>
<h4 class="header"><i>1.3.3</i>Latin rectangles<a class="headerlink" href="#latin-rectangles" name="latin-rectangles">&para;</a></h4>
<p>Extending to a square: <span>$X$</span> = columns, <span>$Y$</span> = numbers. Edge between column and number if the number is not in the column. Results in a <span>$(n-r)$</span> regular graph, decomposes into PMs, make those into new rows.</p>
<h4 class="header"><i>1.3.4</i>Edge colouring<a class="headerlink" href="#edge-colouring" name="edge-colouring">&para;</a></h4>
<p>Bipartite graph: <span>$\chi^E(G) = \Delta(G)$</span> (max deg); proof by adding dummy edges until it's <span>$d$</span>-regular and then decomposing</p>
<h4 class="header"><i>1.3.5</i>Systems of distinct representatives<a class="headerlink" href="#systems-of-distinct-representatives" name="systems-of-distinct-representatives">&para;</a></h4>
<p>SDR exists <span>$\iff$</span> union of any sets <span>$\geq$</span> size of any one set. Proof by Hall's.</p>
<h4 class="header"><i>1.3.6</i>The house-selling problem<a class="headerlink" href="#the-house-selling-problem" name="the-house-selling-problem">&para;</a></h4>
<p>Bipartite graph. Find a perfect matching. If you can't, find an unsuppliable set <span>$A \subseteq X$</span>; increase house prices in <span>$\Gamma(A)$</span> and decrease house prices of undemanded houses; continue until PM is found.</p>
<h4 class="header"><i>1.3.7</i>Telecommunication networks<a class="headerlink" href="#telecommunication-networks" name="telecommunication-networks">&para;</a></h4>
<p>Crossbar: <span>$N$</span> inputs/outputs; <span>$N^2$</span> connections, <span>$O(N^4)$</span> crossovers.</p>
<p>Clos: <span>$r$</span> <span>$n\times m$</span>, then <span>$m$</span> <span>$r\times r$</span>, then <span>$r$</span> <span>$m \times n$</span>. Fewer connections, fewer crossovers. If <span>$m=2n-1$</span>, all packets can be routed online. For offline routing, create a bipartite graph, edge between <span>$(i, \pi_i)$</span>, use Hall's.</p>
<h4 class="header"><i>1.3.8</i>König-Egerváry<a class="headerlink" href="#konig-egervary" name="konig-egervary">&para;</a></h4>
<p>Largest matching = smallest vertex cover</p>
<h2 class="header"><i>2</i>Planar graphs<a class="headerlink" href="#planar-graphs" name="planar-graphs">&para;</a></h2>
<h3 class="header"><i>2.1</i>Euler's formula<a class="headerlink" href="#eulers-formula" name="eulers-formula">&para;</a></h3>
<p><span>$m+2=n+f$</span>. Proof by induction: base case = tree; otherwise, cycle - remove an edge and apply IH.</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>2.2</i>Other formulas<a class="headerlink" href="#other-formulas" name="other-formulas">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Any planar graph: <span>$m \leq 3n-6$</span> for <span>$n \geq 4$</span>. Proof: by Euler. An edge has at most 2 faces; face has at least 3 edges.</p>
<p>Bipartite planar graph: <span>$m \leq 2n-4$</span>. There are no odd cycles, so, any face has at least 4 edges.</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>2.3</i>Platonic solids<a class="headerlink" href="#platonic-solids" name="platonic-solids">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Only 5. Proof: Euler's formula, using <span>$2m=n \cdot d$</span> (cus regular) and <span>$2m=f\cdot p$</span> (cus an edge has 2 faces).</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>2.4</i>Vertex-colouring<a class="headerlink" href="#vertex-colouring" name="vertex-colouring">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Six-colourability proof: using Euler's, min degree <span>$&lt; 6$</span>; remove, apply IH, add back.</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>2.5</i>Art gallery theorem<a class="headerlink" href="#art-gallery-theorem" name="art-gallery-theorem">&para;</a></h3>
<p><span>$n$</span> walls <span>$\to$</span> <span>$\lfloor n/3 \rfloor$</span> guards. Proof: split up floor into triangle, prove 3-colourability by induction.</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>2.6</i>Planar duals<a class="headerlink" href="#planar-duals" name="planar-duals">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Swap faces and vertices.</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>2.7</i>Graph minors<a class="headerlink" href="#graph-minors" name="graph-minors">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Contracting edges is basically all you need. Equivalent to contracting trees.</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>2.8</i>Kuratowski's theorem<a class="headerlink" href="#kuratowskis-theorem" name="kuratowskis-theorem">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Planar <span>$\iff$</span> no <span>$K_3$</span> or <span>$K_{5,5}$</span> minor. Proof by minimum counterexample.</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>2.9</i>Fáry's theorem<a class="headerlink" href="#farys-theorem" name="farys-theorem">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Any planar graph has a straight line drawing. Proof by induction?</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>2.10</i>Menger's theorem<a class="headerlink" href="#mengers-theorem" name="mengers-theorem">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Max flow min cut basically</p>
<h2 class="header"><i>3</i>Probability<a class="headerlink" href="#probability" name="probability">&para;</a></h2>
<h3 class="header"><i>3.1</i>Union and intersection<a class="headerlink" href="#union-and-intersection" name="union-and-intersection">&para;</a></h3>
<p><span>$$P(A \cup B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A \cap B)$$</span></p>
<h3 class="header"><i>3.2</i>Conditional<a class="headerlink" href="#conditional" name="conditional">&para;</a></h3>
<p><span>$$P(A|B) = \frac{P(A \cap B)}{P(B)}$$</span></p>
<h3 class="header"><i>3.3</i>Bayes' theorem<a class="headerlink" href="#bayes-theorem" name="bayes-theorem">&para;</a></h3>
<p><span>$$P(A|B) = \frac{P(B|A)\cdot P(A)}{P(B)}$$</span></p>
<h3 class="header"><i>3.4</i>Discrete random variables<a class="headerlink" href="#discrete-random-variables" name="discrete-random-variables">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Linearity of expectation: <span>$E(aX + bY) = aE(X) + bE(Y)$</span></p>
<p>For independent events: <span>$E(XY) = E(X)E(Y)$</span></p>
<h3 class="header"><i>3.5</i>Binomial distribution<a class="headerlink" href="#binomial-distribution" name="binomial-distribution">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Bernouilli trial: success with prob <span>$p$</span>.</p>
<p><span>$$\binom{n}{k} = \frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}$$</span></p>
<h3 class="header"><i>3.6</i>Random walks<a class="headerlink" href="#random-walks" name="random-walks">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Markov chain model. Just matrix multiplication. Stationary distribution with <span>$d_v/2m$</span> for any <span>$v$</span>.</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>3.7</i>Markov's inequality<a class="headerlink" href="#markovs-inequality" name="markovs-inequality">&para;</a></h3>
<p><span>$$P(Z &gt; c \cdot E(Z)) \leq \frac{1}{c}$$</span></p>
<h3 class="header"><i>3.8</i>Chernoff bounds<a class="headerlink" href="#chernoff-bounds" name="chernoff-bounds">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Ind. Bernouilli trials <span>$X = X_1 + X_2 + \ldots + X_j$</span>, <span>$\mu = E(X)$</span>. Then:</p>
<p><span>$$P(X &gt; (1+\delta)\mu) \leq \left ( \frac{e^\delta}{(1+\delta)^{(1+\delta)}} \right )^\mu$$</span></p>
<p>Proof: let <span>$f(x) = e^{tx}$</span> for some <span>$t$</span>, apply to both sides of inequality of LHS. Use Markov's, simply with <span>$p$</span>. Use the fact that <span>$1+x \leq e^x$</span> (or <span>$1-x \leq e^{-x}$</span> for the <span>$&lt;$</span> inequality). Take the deriv of the exponent, set to 0 to find <span>$t$</span>.</p>
<p>Corollary: <span>$1 &gt; \delta &gt; 0$</span>, <span>$P(X &gt; (1+\delta)\mu)  \leq e^{-1/3\mu\delta^2}$</span>. Proof by Taylor series.</p>
<p>Another: <span>$b \geq 6 \mu$</span>, <span>$P(X &gt; b) \leq 2^{-b}$</span>. Proof since <span>$2e &lt; 6$</span>.</p>
<h2 class="header"><i>4</i>Combinatorics<a class="headerlink" href="#combinatorics" name="combinatorics">&para;</a></h2>
<h3 class="header"><i>4.1</i>Calatan numbers<a class="headerlink" href="#calatan-numbers" name="calatan-numbers">&para;</a></h3>
<p>+-+-+ etc with each partial sum (from the left) being positive.</p>
<p><span>$$C(n) = \frac{1}{n+1} \binom{2n}{n}$$</span></p>
<p>Proof: Using <span>$D(n)$</span>, the reflection thing, etc.</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>4.2</i>Generating functions<a class="headerlink" href="#generating-functions" name="generating-functions">&para;</a></h3>
<h4 class="header"><i>4.2.1</i>Ordinary<a class="headerlink" href="#ordinary" name="ordinary">&para;</a></h4>
<p>For counting labelled objects</p>
<p><span>$$F(x) = \sum_{n \geq 0} f(x) x^n$$</span></p>
<h3 class="header"><i>4.3</i>Exponential<a class="headerlink" href="#exponential" name="exponential">&para;</a></h3>
<p>For counting unlabelled objects</p>
<p><span>$$F(x) = \sum_{n \geq 0} f(x) \frac{x^n}{x!}$$</span></p>
<h3 class="header"><i>4.4</i>Binomial theorem<a class="headerlink" href="#binomial-theorem" name="binomial-theorem">&para;</a></h3>
<p><span>$$(1+x)^n = \sum_{k=0}^n \binom{n}{k} x^k$$</span></p>
<p>Generalised: let <span>$\displaystyle \binom{n}{k} = \frac{n \cdot (n-1)\cdots (n-k+1)}{k!}$</span></p>
	
